<html>
  <head>
    <title>Hadoop EC2 Cluster</title>
  </head>
  
  <body>
    <h1>Hadoop EC2 Cluster</h1>
    To browse the cluster you need to have a proxy configured.
    Start the proxy with <tt>hadoop-ec2 proxy &lt;cluster_name&gt;</tt>,
    and point your browser to
    <a href="http://cloudera-public.s3.amazonaws.com/ec2/proxy.pac">this Proxy
      Auto-Configuration (PAC)</a> file.  To manage multiple proxy configurations,
    you may wish to use
    <a href="https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/2464">FoxyProxy</a> along with a persistent tunnel to the hadoop master node:
    <pre style="font-size:10px"><code>
        ssh -i PATH/TO/KEYPAIR/KEY.pem  -N -D 6666 -o StrictHostKeyChecking=no -o "ConnectTimeout=10" -o "ServerAliveInterval=60" -o "ControlPath=none" root@<%= node[:ec2][:public_hostname] %>
    </code></pre>   
    <ul>
      <!-- FIXME: this is incorrect if the webfront isn't the jobtracker and namenode. Or if you're not on ec2 -->
      <li><a href="http://<%= node[:ec2][:public_hostname] %>:50070/">NameNode</a>
      <li><a href="http://<%= node[:ec2][:public_hostname] %>:50030/">JobTracker</a>
      <!-- Uncomment if you use cloudera Desktop -->
      <!-- <li><a href="http://<%= node[:ec2][:public_hostname] %>:8088/">Cloudera Desktop</a> -->
    </ul>
  </body>
  
</html>
